text.text: A Guide to Notting Hill

From race riots in the '60s to Julia Roberts in the '90s, this colourful corner of West London has seen all sorts over the years. It's a place where a vibrant (yet diminishing) Caribbean community coexists with fat cats and washed up celebs; where seemingly vacant palatial mansions rise high and a low key street party takes place once a year.

We've turned up to find out whether the rumours are true: is this place really just full of yummy mummies indulging in crazy long brunches whilst the day slips lazily on by? Yeah, mostly.
Best for... a cheap Neapolitan eat

tip.text:
Amidst the madness enveloping Notting Hill Gate is a scruffy Neapolitan gem: the kind of neighbourhood trattoria with a charm to it that’s almost magnetic. Run by the super friendly (and Napoli mad) Ruocco family, it’s been operating in this small nook since 1980 which is frankly quite nuts given W11’s evolving nature. It does pizza. It does pasta. It does a banging tiramisu.

It’s a local favourite and it’s easy to see why. All the tasty Neapolitan pizzas and soothing pastas come in at less than a tenner - yet the quality is unrivalled. From the humble, rough and ready trattoria aesthetics to the friendly family vibes to the homemade recipes, this place has all kinds of things going for it. And if you really want to see it in full flow, come on a night when Napoli are playing.

Run by the super friendly (and Napoli mad) Ruocco family, it’s been operating in this small nook since 1980: it does Neapolitan pizzas, it does soothing pasta, it does a banging tiramisu; all for UNDER A TENNER! That's madness in W11. From the rough and ready trattoria aesthetics, to the friendly family vibes, to the homemade recipes, this place is a real local hero.
Best for... a cafe with some character

tip.text:
Haminados is just the kind of eccentric and cosy cafe that could become a favourite. The gregarious (potentially overly so) Greek owner Joseph has been here for nearly fifteen years running this place and he does it his way: a mixture of homemade deli-style grub and shit loads of memorabilia.

Mediterranean bites sit alongside bagels, sandwiches and salads in the kitchen, but on the walls is where the real action happens: a bizarrely captivating interior that resembles a joint fan-club HQ of the Beatles, Grease and Mamma Mia. Once you've taken it in, head out back to the little sun trap garden: an ideal place for sipping on a cappuccino with a slice of cherry pie.

Best for... kitschy cocktails

tip.text: Aloha Booza! Yes here we have it: a hidden tiki basement lounge which might just be the kitschiest thing we've ever laid eyes upon. And we don't mean that as a criticism - this place is dope: with a 60s playlist, super friendly staff in Hawaiian shirts doing all they can to keep you happy and potentially the most original cocktails in these ends, all at around the £10 mark. Tuck yourself into one of their booths and let that good-time vibe soak into your skin.

Best for... a feel good brunch

tip.text:
Brunch is big business in these ends and Farmacy is a definite hotspot - where big old queues have been known to form on weekends and where you feel like a minor celebrity might be walking through the door at any moment. It's in the mould of numerous places around here with Scandi-inspired decor, all manner of plants, and hordes of yummy mummies leisurely indulging in some grub with their gossip. It's slightly pricey, too, it must be said.

Everything on the menu is plant-based: sustainable, organic... all that good shit. But the menu is by no means a dull health fix: they aren't counting calories here and there are all kinds of treats including their sweet rawnola, a delicious protein pancake, and a super take on nachos.

tip.text:
Tucked away on a very chilled residential street, Ladbroke Arms is the kind of unassuming neighbourhood boozer perfect for a break from the hustle. Inside it's a country tip: heavy woods, patterned wallpaper and deep dark ales. Perhaps the kind of place you'd meet in before you went on a fox hunt. Jk - it would be after the fox hunt, when their huge wine list would help ease the guilt.

As for the food, the grub on offer here better reflects that of a restaurant than a pub, and although it's not cheap, you'll understand why after one bite of your roasted cod with Israeli couscous, tomatoes, olives, coriander & lemon oil.

Our favourite thing about this place, though, is the outside. Here hanging baskets full of flowers come into bloom in the summer and the benches become hot property, with locals spilling out onto the road holding their pints; the sinking sun to the west creating a perfect backdrop.

tip.text: Sure, the prices are kind of steep but this isn't the place for your weekly flick: this is the place for those push-the-boat-all-the-way-out-so-you-can't-even-see-land-anymore-type occasions. When you're seeking to woo someone/leave the dog house. There are 65 leather armchairs with footstools and side tables, 3 two-seater sofas and cashmere blankets; there are even six double beds at the front. This is something swish, something swanky and sometimes, you need a bit of that with your movie.

tip.text:
Whilst the pristine decor and staff uniforms might make this place feel a little chainy, this is most certainly a family business: a rich and decadent dose of Italo-indulgence coming all the way from Bologna. Backed by a couple of ex-Chelsea players (Gianfranco Zola and Roberto Di Matteo), the family behind this basically took the best gelato, coffee and cake recipes from their home city and brought them to W11.

We're mighty glad about that. The gelato - made in house - is creamy and rich and taking a bite of their lemon tart with a sip of their coffee is straight-up euphoria. Expect this place to get real busy come sunshine time.

Best for... a farmyard dinner

tip.text:
'From farm to table' is the ethos of this colourful, lively eatery accurately named The Shed. Opened by some bros in their mid-20s (!!), this snug spot mixes fancy dining with a lively vibe to create a great shout for a special dine out. Colourful oil drums act as tables, tractor parts as wall decorations and the bathroom has some pretty fetching farmyard wallpaper. It's enough to have you momentarily thinking of a simpler, more rural lyf.

But food here is a serious business: divided into 'mouthfuls', 'slow cooking' and 'fast cooking', treats vary from the intriguing (mushroom marmite) to the downright sublime (venison cigars with mayo and tarragon). And it's not too hard on the wallet either, given the quality.

tip.text:
Those down-under folk really know their way around an espresso machine. Farm Girl is a perfect example of what an Aussie can do when combining food, drink, and art to make a seriously chilled hang-out spot.

An ode to Melbourne and an ode to coconuts, this sunny Notting Hill haven is fast becoming a West London fave. The walls are decorated with awesome shiny blue tiles, the courtyard is a cosy sun trap and the food is ‘holistic and healthy’. Don’t let that last bit put you off, as the food is delicious (and nutritious) - try superfood smoothies, white Devon crab cakes and the millet porridge topped with all kinds of seeds, omega mix, and bee pollen(?!). Tired of your regular old cappuccino? Why not go for something more adventurous like a liquid gold latte with turmeric, cinnamon, astralagus, and honey.

text.text:
Errr, yeah, it's another brunch spot, but we did warn you. Aussies roam around these ends without supervision and on this patch of land they've even been permitted to set up an ode to Melbourne's chilled cafe culture. The food is, of course, healthy and holistic, the courtyard is a cosy sun trap and they have awesome shiny turquoise tiles. 

The pace here is slow: the idea being you take your time with that superfood smoothie, those Devon crab cakes, that millet porridge topped with all manner of strange ingredients. Nice food, nice hang out spot.
Best for... a venue with legacy

tip.text:
NHAC really is an institution around these parts, with the floors and walls soaked in a pretty pungent mixture of sweat, tears and musical legacy. The likes of Bryson Tiller, Nas and Disclosure have graced the stage in recent years, but now it's a lot more about themed club nights, where DJs spin vinyl and everything from old school garage nights to Drake specials take place. A late night, no-frills place for a shakedown, which are by no means plentiful around here.

Be warned these guys are crazy strict on ID no matter your age, so make sure you got it (or a photo of it).

listing.name: The Fish House of Notting Hill
listing.subtitle: Proper Fish & Chips

tip.text:
A few years ago these guys set out to establish themselves as the best place for fish & chips in London, and while we’re wary of confirming such a sweeping statement, if local regulars include the Beckhams then you probably aren’t doing a terrible job of things. This is a traditional chippie and you’ll see vintage, kind of tacky, photos of London on the walls here to remind you of the dish’s heritage.

Fish & chips may well be a British staple, but the fish used here comes from Norway, and Ash recommends the cod (we concur). Beers and wines are on offer here, too, making it a little sophisticated chippy. Expect lots of tourists on weekends.

tip.text: Dropping in here is kind of like visiting the rustic pantry of a middle-class mum's house, where the cupboards are always stocked and she's cool with you spending the entire afternoon in there because you've got nowhere to be. It's all-day dining, but brunch, and its egg variations, is certainly centre stage: they feature in everything from the humble scrambled egg on toast to super comforting dishes like the sweet potato rosti with poached egg, goat's cheese, honey, kale and dill yoghurt. This place is built for comfort and fuelling: perfect for a post-yoga bite, if you do yoga (and if you live in these ends, you do).

Best for... a pretty pint

tip.text:
Damn this is a pretty pub. It's as old as the hills (meaning the 1820s), and they've happily made a real effort to maintain those dope Victorian stylings. That means super low doorways, beautiful dark wood everywhere and cosy little cubbyholes featuring a sherry bar, a roaring fire and jovial west Londoners sipping on ales.

The classics are all on show in the kitchen (fish and chips, steak sandwiches etc) but at slightly gastro-inflated prices, naturally. But Venison steak with orange marmalade jus, braised red cabbage & heritage potatoes is gonna cost you pal, especially when the quality is excellent and portion sizes generous. When you throw in a heated beer garden, it's no surprise that this is a popular little spot. Reserving is a necessity.
